## Archiving With Retrofit

By default, Retrofit will use a cache interceptor to intercept requests and save them to temporary cache in memory. This is especially useful when dealing with APIs that have lots of static content that you don’t want to repeatedly get from the server. If the saved content does not change, you can simply ask the Retrofit cache for the content. This is very helpful when presenting information in an application or showing a list on a dialog without going through the main activity/screen. More common use cases would include offering offline dictionary word definition lookups, as well as providing a collection of commonly used (or useless) URL resources as dynamically accessible posts, etc.

### Example: offline documentation lookup

CachedRetrofit t = CachedRetrofit.builder()
.build();
IRetrofitAPI_ wiki = t.create(IRetrofitAPI_.class);
Uri uri = Uri.parse("https://source.android.com/documentation/index.html").buildUpon()
.build();
Response response = wiki.getDocumentation(uri);
String x = response.getCachedContent();

### Fetching Cache

You can access the fetched content using the CachedContent interface.
Retrofit implementation will provide the ServerCodec class for Content#cachedContent(), which uses the unmodified request body as the cache key. Cache invalidation is based on the byte range, milliseconds until expiration mark as well as a signature over the body content.

public interface CachedContent {
InputStream cachedContent();
}

### Configuring To Print Azure Appliance Cache Status Command

If you are picking for the common choice to include the cache status in your application logging, simply use the following switch in your retrofit instance to print the contents of the cache area.

Log.w(“RetrofitCache”, “Cache status: ” + cache)

